This bird doesn't usually visit our area on the west coast. We saw one individual in April 2011 and understand that one was seen in 2006. The bird was seen and id verified by local birding expert Chris Dale.

This mother came to our kitchen deck door at dusk with 2 young. The way they behaved suggests someone in our neighbourhood is feeding them. Hmm. I feed birds - in absolute terms some people feel I'm also doing wrong.

These two juveniles were closer in size than they appear in this photograph. The one on the left seems to be making himself look bigger. They came to our kitchen deck at dusk with their mother - likely looking for food.

We have feeders at the front and back of our house. The females often prefer to feed at the quieter front of the house. The males arrive on or about March 26 each year and the females one or two weeks later.

We seldom see warblers at our feeders. This one stayed for 2 days, feeding at the suet. (We normally stop feeding suet a bit earlier in the year to help avoid attracting bears.) Apologies for the quality of the photos: together they show the distinctive characteristics.
Flocks are sometimes reported in the Estuary during the winter. We had a small flock at our feeders for a few days and have not seen them since.
We have seen these every spring consistently at our feeders. For the past 3 years they have nested in our hedge.

Originally I suggested that this is a Swainson's Thrush, and several members of the Community identified it as a juvenile European Starling. Thanks to the helpful link Bridget Spencer posted I can now see why the starling id made sense to people. I consulted with Chris Dale, our local birding expert who is also a neighbour, and his reply was "Judging by the mask across its eye and the slight streaking on the breast I would guess it is an immature Cedar Waxwing." With the under chin so pale I wondered about it being a Bohemian Waxwing, but their breeding range looks to be north of us. Waxwing seems like a reasonable option: too bad we can't see the tail!
These finches nest near our yard every summer.

A biologist friend identified this as a PCF (Pacific chorus frog) which I understand is the same as the Pacific Tree Frog. It and 4 others ended up in my garage after I brought in a pile of tree clippings from a dogwood.  I searched the garage to make sure I'd found all and released them. Since then I have not seen any in my garden.

When it gets cold and snowy the Varied Thrushes visit our back yard. They often copy the other birds at our feeders. This one had been trying to eat at our suet feeder and then decided to take a break and rest on our porch railing.
We most often have bears in our yard in spring when natural food sources are not plentiful. This bear looked like a yearling, in its first season without its mother.

The black form of the Eastern Grey Squirrel is more common than the grey in our neighbourhood, but we regard all forms as invasive. They have spread through our area since having been introduced in Vancouver in 1914. I do not know about the impact on native plant species, but I do see the interaction between the black squirrels and our native Douglas Squirrels. The larger black squirrels drive the native squirrels away from preferred food sources.

This young bird approached me this morning as I was putting out feeders. He looked like he was very recently fledged and I was surprised to see the pink markings of a male on such a young bird. Such a young bird so late in October seems unusual. I understand that some species have second clutches if the food supply is good but this seems late even for a second clutch.
The Berberis plants in my garden grow under cedar trees and I believe they have been seeded via bird droppings. The blooms look like tiny daffodils when viewed close-up.

Apologies to Bird0_1 who id'ed my earlier observation, which I deleted because I had trouble adding new/better photos. The individual bird has been in our area since September and has recently been visiting a feeder rigged up with a trouble light to keep it warm during our colder and snowy weather. I do not know whether this individual is an adult female or a juvenile. It seems very large when compared to the Rufous hummingbirds who frequent our feeders in summer.

I saw this tiny green bug when I was photographing pollinators. The only tiny green bugs I knew were aphids, and I understand that this is not an aphid. I queried on Bugguide whether this was a Lygus lineolarius (because I saw that id suggested for a photo from Oregon of a similar-looking bug).  I've added the Bugguide link below even though I do not have an id.  Ken Volgemuth said: "Lygus looks right but I wouldn't venture a guess as to species." The article at http://entnemdept.ufl.edu/creatures/trees/tarnished_plant_bug.htm describes the Tarnished Plant bug species as damaging conifer seedlings, and includes a photo of a 4th or 5th stage nymph. To my uninformed eye it looks similar to my bug which has the dark spot on the abdomen and at least some on the thorax.
This bee was on a daisy in late afternoon.

Dr Ascher reviewed this photograph and identified the bee as Bombus caliginosus or vosnesenskii. I understand that the distinction depends in part on the presence or absence of yellow hairs on the underside of the abdomen, and of course I don't have a photograph that helps with this.

This tiny snail was underneath a rotten beam I moved in my garden. I could see the creature moving inside the shell but once I had my camera it was not interested in emerging and posing for me. 

I'm just guessing at the id - there seem to be several species of glass snails, all introduced?

Bees like this have already been working at this white heather plant in my garden for a couple of weeks. It seems so early for bees. 

Bugguide had no report for this species for BC for March.
This bird was with a flock of about 50 of the juncos that we usually see: with - dark hood and reddish-brown sides and back

Today we have a pair of these in our backyard, feeding alongside a flock of juncos, with some White-crowned sparrows. We usually see the Golden-crowns for a couple of days each spring as they migrate to nesting grounds.

This was our first male black-headed grosbeak of the season, yesterday evening. He stayed briefly to feed. I also saw a female but she did not stay to feed. We usually have several pairs nesting in the area near our feeders.
This morning we have both the male and the female black-headed grosbeaks at our feeders.

This insect was on a Mountain Ash leaf. It was pretty windy when I  took the photo so I wasn't able to get good focus before it left the stage. Unlikely we'll be able to get a species from this photo?
About a week ago we had a small flock of Evening Grosbeaks briefly visit our feeders. Since then we have had a pair visit several times. Here is the male: I will post the female separately.
This bird was very skittish. She visited our feeders in company with a male (see separate observation). We had a male and a female several days recently so it could have been this pair.
This beetle was hiding under a heather plant, in the middle of decaying organic material. The beautiful turquoise accents caught my eye.
Our visits from the Band-tailed pigeons are short and infrequent because our feeders are set up so that they are not able to vacuum all the seed.
This bird does not have the developed white collar and therefore I'm guessing it's a juvenile.
Another find under heather plant while I was gardening. I posted on Bugguide and got no suggestions.  However, from photos on that site, it seems to me that this is Armadillidium vulgare.

Yesterday evening at close to dusk our feeders hosted a pair of Black-capped chickadees and three fledglings. We don't usually see chickadees at our feeders in the summer. We have never before seen chickadee fledglings being fed seed: finch fledglings of various species are common for us a bit later in the year. This is the only usable photo I was able to get. I tried for the three lined up together on this branch in a classic pose, but the light was very low and I wasn't successful.
On a peony bloom.

This year the Varied Thrushes came to our yard and feeders during our first cold snap and a few have stayed despite the warmer weather and absence of snow. We have heavy snow forecast so no doubt the number in our yard will increase. One winter we had 16 - this year the maximum we have seen is 7.

description: The icy snow on the trunk of the alder masked some of shape of the "fans", but the ?fluted edges of the fans show. I realize that the jelly fungi are hard to identify, but these look to me very much like benkeen's observation 37048647.

For the past two weeks we have been visited by a large flock of pine siskins - 100 or more. This is unusual for us, especially in winter. The photo of the tree against the dark sky shows a small part of the flock.

We found this hair ice at a higher elevation than our previous observations near the Mamquam River. It was the first time I had seen the ice on a standing tree trunk, likely a red alder, rather than on or close to the ground.

This polypore seems to be dead - it was woody and very crumbly when I broke a piece off to show a profile. It was about 20 cm across, on the ground about 2 m from the trunk of a large western hemlock.  There were at least 4 layers (?pileus) concentric. The rosette effect suggested Phaeolus schweinitzii, but the surface seemed to match the "soft velvety" described for O. tomentosa. Not easy to tell with such an old specimen.
A few of these birds visited our feeders at this time. I understand small flocks visit the Squamish Estuary some winters, but they seldom come uphill to our property.

The nests are mug-shaped, with a brownish interior, height 1 cm width 1 cm. Older specimens turn darker brown.  "Eggs" containing spores seem already to have dispersed, so it is not possible to describe them.  I will try to watch next year for young specimens. The white exterior seems to be one characteristic distinguishing this species from N. candida.

These photos were taken on a single alder, within about a metre of the trunk. I'm wondering whether there is more than one type of fungus here. The "mat" caught my eye first, and then I saw the brackets with the brown stripes and finally the brackets with some yellow on them. The undersides suggest the id to me, but I could find no motion of the dark surfaces, partly hairy.

Close to the Merrill Park Summit trailhead there are many specimens of this fungus, growing on cut ends of logs on the forest floor.  These photos show an older example. I will post a younger one from nearby separately.

Close to the Merrill Park Summit trailhead there are many specimens of this fungus, growing on cut ends of logs on the forest floor. These photos show younger examples. I have posted an older one from nearby separately.
These lichens were surrounded by Cladonia bellidiflora, just about the only Cladonia I am confident in identifying. At this stage, I don't know the best id.

I remembered after @judithofsquamish queried one the photos I originally posted with this observation that I had found two separate areas of lichens on the trunk of a mature hemlock. The first area I found I concluded was C. macilenta  and then went back with a better camera to try for better shots. At that time I found an area closer to the ground, with much more pronounced red apothecia and patches of scales close by. Looking at others' observations I concluded that must be C. bellidiflora and forgot about my earlier conclusion. I have now created a separate observation for C. macilenta based on my first photographs and hope this all makes more sense.

I dug back to find this record shot I took the fall we had large numbers of Evening Grosbeaks frequenting our feeders. There are at least 10 here. Since then we see 2 or 3 once or twice per year, now that grosbeaks are considered threatened.
Our first robins of the year showed up this past week. We are having colder temperatures and it looks like they are having a tough time finding food.

The range of these doves has spread considerably over the past 50 years. It seems that they are common in the valley below here we live, but we don't often see them in our backyard. They are quite skittish when it comes to feeding with other birds, even though they are relatively large.

I remembered after @judithofsquamish queried one the photos I originally posted with an observation of C. bellidiflora that I had found two separate areas of lichen on the trunk of a mature hemlock. I have now created this separate observation for C. macilenta based on my first photographs and hope this all makes more sense.

I thought this must be fungal growth on the alders I observed. The lesions appeared to be regularly spaced, and in cracks in the bark they had become much larger. The plant clinic at Oregon State University describes Cytospora (Diaporthe) stem canker of red alder and their photo shows the only similar growths I was able to find. . "Note the extruded coils of spores called cirri coming from pycnidia in the bark." https://pnwhandbooks.org/plantdisease/host-disease/alder-alnus-spp-canker-stem-diseases This seems to be the most likely kind of disease to match what I saw. There are no photos in iNat to review for comparison purposes.
This moss is growing enthusiastically in the open centres of paving stones in our yard.

This rock caught my eye because of the unusual colours. It is in an area which has been logged within the past twenty years (or so) and where trails and access roads have been built. Most rock we see there has no visible lichen. At first I thought the rock was rust-coloured with light crust lichen with some algae. When I looked at the photos I realized that there is also rusty-brown lichen and there are a lot of interesting irregularities which make me think there could be many species here. There are some pinkish forms that look very much like ascidians I have seen intertidally. I'm guessing it's unlikely we will be able to id anything from photos but if anyone would like to see sharp close-ups I can go back with better camera gear.

description: This little beetle was moving quickly. I found in the Austin Bug Collection http://www.austinbug.com/coccinellidae2.html information on a characteristic of this variable species: "the pronotum, which usually has a black pattern that looks like a W or an M, depending on your orientation. This pattern can be very light and thin, or it can swell so that most of the pronotum is black. When it is not obscured, the center part of the W or M is thinner than the outer parts. The outer sides of the pronotum almost always have large white marks (yes, there are sometimes exceptions to this, too, but not often)." This beetle had markings that seem to fit.

I opened a bag of locally-produced compost after having had it covered over the winter. I was startled to see this brilliant green mold. I realize that there are thousands of green molds, including Penicillium, Cladosporium and Aspergillus. This comes from  https://donotdisturbgardening.com/why-does-my-compost-have-mold/ "Green mold is seen in compost with a lot of food waste. Green mold is also a sign of too much moisture in the bin, so keep a balance of dry to wet ingredients. Green mold spreads fast as it digests nitrogen-carbon compounds in food scraps."

Most bees I see in my garden now look like this one.  I have been trying to photograph the "fringe of yellow hairs at S4" on the underside of the abdomen of these bees to show that they are Bombus caliginosus. I photograph only live specimens that are in normal conditions. From Bugguide: "To the north, especially at the coast, both species (B. caliginosus and B. vosnesenkii) could occur and ID is very difficult at best from images alone as these can be difficult to separate even with specimens. (Comment by John S. Ascher)." This photo interested me because it shows pale striping on the abdomen above the yellow stripe.  I am adding a second photo to show a side view, even though there is no hope of showing the fringe with it.

This fungus is quite rubbery and thin and was growing on a fallen hardwood log. When I peeled away a small piece, there was a strong "mushroomy  smell". The underside is black. From the side it seems to show black rings, perhaps signs of annual growth? Thanks to @benkeen for posting several observations of this species - this id is following his lead.

I have included three photos because I don't know the characteristic features for this bee. I can't find anything that has this type of hair, so can't even venture a guess. Thanks for any suggestions.

This was new to me. ENField on Bugguide pointed me to Tachinidae. From there I reviewed photos and found some similarities with Peleteria subgenus sphyrimyia (observations 128698 and 637800 in Bugguide). However, Bugguide does not seem to have any records for BC. Thanks for taking time to help me with this.
Andrena is a guess for genus - nothing more. Suggestions always appreciated!
The dark, bulbous abdomen is leading to my id. Another guess, based on very sketchy knowledge, and with the help of photos on Bugguide.

This "bee" was another surprize. I was trying to get a good photo of a Black-tailed bumble bee and didn't even notice the detail of this "bee". The body is short and squat compared to most of the bees we're seeing, and I just don't know what to suggest.

My notes say that this bee was very small, compared to the others in my garden at the time. I have not been able to find a striping pattern that matches this bee's abdomen. Any suggestions will be gratefully received. 
Noted later: orange-coloured parasites in thorax? (Saw this several times on this species, same location, summer 2021.)

We contacted Wild Birds Unlimited in Vancouver and were told that one individual had recently been reported in North Vancouver so perhaps this was the same bird. When I asked our local birders about this visitor, one recalled a sighting in 2006.  These birds are normally not seen on the west side of the Coast Range in our area. It fed, had some water, and was gone within the hour, so I felt fortunate to have seen it and to have captured some record shots.

I am interested in taking photos of live bees that could help distinguish B. vosnesenskii from B. caliginosus in our area. There are no recent records for the latter species in BC. I do understand the challenges, but  "nothing ventured, nothing gained". Overall the individual has a shaggy appearance. I appreciate any thoughts you have.

description: I understand that this species thrives in highly acidic soil, which is what we have given all the western red cedar trees in our yards.

I am following Pojar and Mackinnon, which notes that P. britannica is distinguished from P. aphthosa by the cephalodia (flecks) being "readily dislodged by the flick of a fingernail". The white spot in the second photo shows where I applied the flick test. Also, P. aphthosa is stated as being "rare in coastal localities".   The lichen is bright green because it has been wet for some time.

description: The deteriorating purple/blue centre on this lichen helps me better understand lichens I observed as https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/68068867 and https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/67933457 . Both were on downed or rotting conifers. This is on hardwood, but with part of the lichen in better condition, it is possible to suggest a species.

We have had hawks swooping through our back garden throughout this past winter. My impression has been that we were seeing Cooper's hawks, mostly juveniles, with their proportionately long tails. I'm guessing this is a Cooper's. The photos are poor and unfortunately don't show the tip of the tail. Perhaps the rufous colouring on the head helps with the id? Only other possible id I can think of would be a (considerably smaller) Sharp-shinned, and I defer to experts!

description: This beetle was hanging on to some grass and waving for dear life in the Squamish sunny day wind. Hence not great detail. Merrill Peterson's PNW Insects shows a similar overall specimen photo as D. backii and about the only characteristic I can match is the flared pronotum. BugGuide describes D. backii as being the most common species in BC but I could find no observations.

Position approximate. This plant is right beside the trail in a steep area where there are mountain bikes and lots of dogs so I wanted to record it now in case it is further damaged. 

Update June 12: I have been watching for blooms. Today I found that the stem had been snapped off because a branch fell beside it, possibly because of a dog running beside the trail. Whatever had been munching on the leaves before this photo was taken had continued to munch. About 1/3 of the leaves had been eaten.

Position approximate. I have found what I believe to be P. orbiculata nearby, and am puzzled by this plant. I can't figures out how it could have 6 leaves, unless there are 3 plants growing concentrically. There was one bloom last year and there is no sign of a bloom this year. I'm hoping that someone can recognize the fruits. This site is very safe from arbitrary damage.

Chamaenerion angustifolium in the Onagraceae (evening primrose) family (genus called Epilobium in our lab but research tells me this is the old name)

- reproductive: inferior ovary, 4 free sepals, 4 free petals, 8 stamens, actinomorphic, fruit a long capsule 
- vegetative: leaves are simple, leaf arrangement alternate to opposite

Habitat:

description: This bee was considerably later than I had seen previously - normally they are on my Lamb's ears from June through August. Bees in Your Backyard mentions this as characteristic.
iNat suggestion for id. The spider appeared to be starting to wrap small prey.
iNat suggested genus and this species is the only one reported for our region. Widespread and visually similar.
